						               													<description>Road safety educational game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;One of 16 cards is drawn - with typical traffic situations seen from a bike-riding kid's perspective, but with empty roads (no other vehicles or traffic signs, depending on the type of card),&amp;#10;then a small cut-out car or a policeman or a traffic sign or -light is placed onto the card, thus creating a typical situation where the question for the kid is: May I ride further or do I have to stop?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;All players then secretly deploy a white (go) or black (stop) chip. The chips are revealed, then every player explains his choice. Finally the back of the card is revealed to learn which answer is right (the cut-outs are coded to easily find the correct solution). Correct answers win a yellow chip. The player with the most chips receives a cardboard biker medal.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As ten different vehicles (e.g. with different turn signals)/ten traffic signs can be placed on each card the game contains a sum of 160 different situations.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
